SubTopics: Analyze how complex characters, events, and ideas develop and interact over the course of a text to impact meaning.
Content: :ibox:The following problem has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
What does paragraph 2 reveal about the sea-captain?

A.Choice: He expects complete submission from his crew.

B.Choice: He is afraid the sailors might revolt against him.

C.Choice: He has had trouble with disrespectful crew members in the past.

D.Choice: He thinks the sailors are defiant and irresponsible.

Content: How does this speech emphasize the sea-captain's perspective?

A.Choice: He is directing the crew to be industrious.

B.Choice: He is threatening the crew against defying him.

C.Choice: He is warning the crew of the dangers they will face.

D.Choice: He is encouraging the crew to get along with each other.

SubTopics: Determine the meaning of words and phrases as they are used in a text, including figurative and connotative meanings; analyze the cumulative impact of specific word choices on meaning and tone, such as how language evokes a sense of time and place, and how it communicates an informal or formal tone.
Content: :ibox:The following problem has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
In paragraph 3, what did the narrator mean when he said he “had little inclination to join” the men talking on the forecastle?

A.Choice: He didn't have to join them.

B.Choice: He didn't need to join them.

C.Choice: He didn't expect to join them.

D.Choice: He didn't want to join them.

Content: What quotation from the paragraph BEST supports the correct answer in Part A?

A.Choice: “I had now a good opportunity for reflection.”

B.Choice: “I felt for the first time the perfect silence of the sea.”

C.Choice: “I had no right to go”

D.Choice: “I could not but remember”

SubTopics: Analyze how an author's choices concerning text structure, plot structure, and/or time manipulation create effects such as mystery, tension, or surprise.
Content: What effect does the first sentence of paragraph 4 create in the passage?

A.Choice: It suggests that the narrator will soon find himself dissatisfied with life at sea.

B.Choice: It provides an explanation for why the narrator has difficulty sleeping.

C.Choice: It signals a shift from the meditative mood of the narrator to a sense of foreboding.

D.Choice: It emphasizes the difference between the narrator and the more experienced sailors.

SubTopics: Analyze how complex characters, events, and ideas develop and interact over the course of a text to impact meaning.
Content: In paragraph 4, what is the significance of the narrator's reaction to the “complete hurrah's nest'” of his belongings in the steerage cabin?

A.Choice: It indicates a realization of the difficult conditions that he will face on the voyage.

B.Choice: It shows that he is reconsidering the wisdom of his choice to become a sailor.

C.Choice: It suggests he will have an even stronger reaction to the more intense scene on deck.

D.Choice: It implies that he has a tendency to give up easily when a situation is beyond his control.

SubTopics: Analyze how point of view and/or author purpose shapes the content and style of diverse texts.
Content: How does having the narrator below deck when the storm strikes affect the plot?

A.Choice: It shows that the narrator is eager to prove himself as a new sailor.

B.Choice: It emphasizes the narrator's inexperience when he is called on deck.

C.Choice: It explains why the narrator feels seasick and is unable to help on deck.

D.Choice: It increases the sense of drama when the narrator goes back on deck.

SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: :ibox:The following problem has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
What is a central idea in the passage?

A.Choice: The narrator fears for his life during the storm.

B.Choice: The narrator is not prepared for life on the ship.

C.Choice: The narrator wishes he hadn't agreed to go to sea.

D.Choice: The narrator believes sailors should be treated better.

Content: Which detail BEST states the central idea?

A.Choice: “I was separating myself from all the social and intellectual enjoyments of life.” (paragraph 3)

B.Choice: “we were allowed no light to find anything with” (paragraph 4)

C.Choice: “drenching us completely through” (paragraph 5)

D.Choice: “I had not got my 'sea legs on'” (paragraph 6)

A.Choice: bleak

B.Choice: resentful

C.Choice: witty

D.Choice: modest

SubTopics: Analyze how an author presents and develops key ideas and events to impact meaning.
Content: How does the author develop the idea that the beauty of commercially grown tomatoes is only “skin deep” (paragraph 4)?

A.Choice: by contrasting the appearance of tomatoes with consumer satisfaction

B.Choice: by explaining how easily tomatoes grown in gardens are bruised and cracked

C.Choice: by comparing how tomatoes look to other commercially grown vegetables

D.Choice: by describing the damage done to commercial vegetables during shipment to market

SubTopics: Analyze how an author's ideas or claims are developed and refined by particular sentences, paragraphs, or larger portions of a text.
Content: Read this sentence from paragraph 4.

:ibox:No one will ever be able to duplicate the flavor of garden-grown fruits and vegetables at the supermarket (or even the farmers' market), but there's a reason you don't hear consumers bemoaning the taste of supermarket cabbages, onions, or potatoes.
How does this sentence help the author develop the idea that commercial farming methods are responsible for consumer dissatisfaction?

A.Choice: The sentence shows that other vegetables have grown more popular in recent years.

B.Choice: The sentence suggests that the quality of other vegetables is much closer to garden fresh.

C.Choice: The sentence cautions against comparing supermarket vegetables to those grown in gardens.

D.Choice: The sentence offers alternative suggestions for purchasing vegetables that taste home grown.

Topics: Reading Information - Integration Of Knowledge & Ideas
SubTopics: Evaluate how reasoning and evidence affects the argument and specific claims in a text.
Content: How does the author support the claim that factory farming has had a larger impact on tomatoes than other vegetables?

A.Choice: by relating information about the quantity of tomatoes grown in Florida

B.Choice: by including a detailed description of how tomatoes are harvested and ripened

C.Choice: by citing statistics that show how satisfaction with tomatoes has declined

D.Choice: by contrasting differences in how tomatoes are farmed to how other vegetables are grown

SubTopics: Determine an author's point of view or purpose and analyze how an author uses rhetoric to advance that point of view or purpose.
Content: How does the author's use of words such as “industrial”, “artificially”, and “factory” help convey his point of view in the passage?

A.Choice: These words are used to illustrate the large impact farming practices have on consumers.

B.Choice: These words imply a loss of the essential qualities associated with traditional farming.

C.Choice: These words highlight the improvements farmers have made to improve crop production.

D.Choice: These words describe how farming practices have enhanced fruits and vegetables.

SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: Which of these statements is the BEST summary?

A.Choice: New commercial farming methods allow consumers to enjoy beautiful, fresh tomatoes even in winter.

B.Choice: Today factory farms produce tomatoes bred to be firmer and fresher than tomatoes grown in the past.

C.Choice: Modern farming techniques have made commercially grown tomatoes inferior to home grown varieties.

D.Choice: Tomatoes grown in home gardens are generally more prone to bruises than those grown commercially.

SubTopics: Determine an author's point of view or purpose and analyze how an author uses rhetoric to advance that point of view or purpose.
Content: What rhetorical strategy does the author use to support his claims about tomatoes?

A.Choice: The author makes an observation about tomatoes based on scientific evidence and observation.

B.Choice: The author compares garden and commercially grown tomatoes and reports his findings objectively.

C.Choice: The author suggests that modern farming methods will begin to impact other vegetables as they have tomatoes.

D.Choice: The author uses personal stories to suggest a theory as to why people are dissatisfied with tomatoes.

Content: Which detail from passage 2 BEST conveys the theme identified in Part A?

A.Choice: “Prometheus did not care to live amid the clouds on the mountain top. He was too busy for that.” (paragraph 5)

D.Choice: He feared that the gods would find out how he helped the people.
